# 9. Level of Nodes
## Medium 
<div class="problem-statement">
                <p></p><p><span style="font-size:18px">Given an Undirected Graph and a node&nbsp;<strong>X</strong>. The task is to find the level of&nbsp;<strong>X&nbsp;</strong>from<strong>&nbsp;0</strong>.</span></p>

<p><br>
<span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Example 1:</strong></span></p>

<pre><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Input:</strong>
</span><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," class="img-responsive"><span style="font-size:18px">
<strong>Output:</strong> 3
<strong>Explanation</strong>: 7th node is in 3rd level
in the given graph above starting from
0th node(source node). </span>
</pre>

<p><br>
<span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Example 2:</strong></span></p>

<pre><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Input:</strong>
</span><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," class="img-responsive"><span style="font-size:18px">
<strong>Output:</strong> 2
<strong>Explanation</strong>: 5th node is in 2nd level
in the given graph above starting from
0th node(source node).
</span></pre>

<p><br>
<span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Your task:</strong><br>
You don’t need to read input or print anything. Your task is to complete the function&nbsp;<strong>levelOfX()</strong>&nbsp;which takes the integer V denoting the number of vertices, X node and adjacency list as input parameters and returns&nbsp;the level of X relative to the node 0. If X does not exist in the graph or is not connected (directly/indirectly)&nbsp;to 0&nbsp;then return -1.</span></p>

<p><br>
<span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Expected Time Complexity:&nbsp;</strong>O(V +&nbsp;E)<br>
<strong>Expected Auxiliary Space:&nbsp;</strong>O(V)</span></p>

<p><br>
<span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Constraints:</strong><br>
1 ≤ V, E ≤ 100<br>
1 ≤ X&nbsp;≤ V</span></p>
 <p></p>
            </div>
